FAQs
What are the top medical schools in Italy?

Some of the top medical schools in Italy include the University of Milan, the University of Bologna, and Sapienza University of Rome.

Is the IMAT exam difficult?

The difficulty of the IMAT exam can vary depending on the student's preparation. Consistent study and practice are key to performing well on the exam.

How much does it cost to study medicine in Italy?

Tuition fees for medical programs in Italy range from €1,000 to €4,000 per year for EU students, with higher fees for non-EU students. Living expenses can range from €700 to €1,200 per month.

Do I need to know Italian to study medicine in Italy?

While many medical programs are offered in English, knowing Italian can be beneficial for interacting with patients and navigating daily life in Italy.

What are the career prospects after studying medicine in Italy?

Graduates from Italian medical schools can pursue careers in Italy and globally. Their degrees are recognized worldwide, allowing them to work in various healthcare settings or continue their education in specialized fields.
